00:00:00.450 --> 00:00:01.540
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hi everyone,
I'm Kat.

00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:04.980
I am with the Authors@Google
program here

00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:06.610
at Google Los Angeles.

00:00:06.610 --> 00:00:07.380
Welcome.

00:00:07.380 --> 00:00:12.900
We're very happy to host
professor Kal Raustiala today.

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:15.450
Professor Raustiala is a
professor at UCLA Law School

00:00:15.450 --> 00:00:19.380
and also a director at Ronald
W. Burkle Center for

00:00:19.380 --> 00:00:22.980
International Relations
at UCLA.

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:25.160
Professor Raustiala is a
graduate of Harvard Law

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:29.260
School, and he is also a
frequent media contributor to

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:32.100
publications like "The Wall
Street Journal," "The New

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:36.910
Yorker," "The New York Times,"
and "The Financial Times." His

00:00:36.910 --> 00:00:39.810
latest book, written with
Christopher Sprigman, is

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:42.440
called "The Knockoff Economy,"
and it was published in

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:45.580
September 2012, this year.

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:47.850
And we're very happy
to have him today.

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:50.980
He's going to talk a little
bit about how copying and

00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:55.680
imitation actually spurs
creativity and innovation.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:57.076
Welcome, professor.

00:00:57.076 --> 00:00:58.534
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:58.534 --> 00:00:59.506
KAL RAUSTIALA: Thank you.

00:00:59.506 --> 00:01:03.394
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:03.394 --> 00:01:06.310
KAL RAUSTIALA: OK,
thanks, everyone.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:10.120
As Kat just said, this book,
which I did write with a

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:14.140
co-author who teaches at UVA,
is really about copyright,

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.710
patent, and how they connect to
innovation and creativity,

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:20.980
so issues that I think would be
of interest here at Google.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:23.220
So I'm really glad to have the
opportunity to come here.

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:24.570
I've never been to
this building.

00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:25.830
I've driven by it
a million times.

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:29.170
So it's great to be here.

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:32.310
Let me start off with a few just
basic points about what

00:01:32.310 --> 00:01:33.670
we try to do in the book.

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:36.680
And then I'm going to run
through some examples to give

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:37.320
you a taste.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:42.820
But the basic gist of the book
is that we are interested in

00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:47.620
how copying affects the
incentives to create and how

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:51.620
it helps sustain or undermine
creativity.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:54.150
So I think, as many of you
know, the underlying idea

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:56.680
behind our intellectual property
system is that

00:01:56.680 --> 00:01:58.230
copying is bad for creativity.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:01:59.950
That's the basic concept.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.250
Copies usually out-compete
originals because they're

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:04.880
cheaper than the originals.

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:08.949
And so we restrict that form of
competition by awarding a

00:02:08.949 --> 00:02:10.550
copyright or a patent.

00:02:10.550 --> 00:02:12.785
I'm going to mostly talk
about copyright today.

00:02:12.785 --> 00:02:15.550
But we restrict that competition
and give the

00:02:15.550 --> 00:02:19.650
originator a window of time in
which they have a monopoly

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:20.960
over that design.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:22.350
So in the case of patent,
it's 20 years.

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:24.140
In the case of copyright, it
sort of depends, but it's

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:25.610
much, much longer.

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:28.780
So that's the basic gist of our
system, and it's been that

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:31.910
way since the framers of the
Constitution first put in a

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:36.000
clause about the need to promote
progress in the useful

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.740
sciences and arts.

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:40.430
So that's the underlying
concept.

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:43.050
So what we're interested in in
this book is not whether or

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:43.760
not that's true.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:46.170
We think that that's generally
true, and we're generally

00:02:46.170 --> 00:02:48.290
supportive of intellectual
property.

00:02:48.290 --> 00:02:51.570
Some people do actually argue
for the abolition of copyright

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:52.470
and patent.

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:53.810
We don't really do that.

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:57.230
But we are interested in whether
it's truly necessary

00:02:57.230 --> 00:03:00.440
to have these copyrights and
patents in place, these

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:03.890
monopoly rights protected by the
government, to have those

00:03:03.890 --> 00:03:06.570
in place to have sustained
creativity.

00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:09.150
When that's true, why it's
true, to what degree it's

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:10.680
true, some of those sorts
of questions.

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.270
And the way that we come at it
in the book is a little bit

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:15.180
different than most work
that's been done.

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:17.910
So a lot of people who look at
these issues focus on things

00:03:17.910 --> 00:03:19.130
like the music industry.

00:03:19.130 --> 00:03:22.180
This has been a hot issue for
a long time, really, ever

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:23.440
since Napster.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.650
And so people have been really
interested in, what happened

00:03:25.650 --> 00:03:28.880
to the music industry,
and is online

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:30.370
downloading a bad thing?

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:31.810
Most people say yes, some
people say it's a

00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:32.750
good thing, et cetera.

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:35.350
They debate it by looking at
copyright-protected industries

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:37.830
or, increasingly, the film and
television industries.

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:40.850
We don't really do that, though
we do have an epilogue

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:42.230
at the end of the book
about music.

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:45.220
What we do instead is look at
industries that don't have

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:47.890
intellectual property
protection, and we try to

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:50.650
understand what happens
in those industries.

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:51.550
How do they operate?

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:54.030
How do they sustain
their innovation?

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:57.500
And those industries are
somewhat unusual.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.970
So I'm going to start off today
with one that I think

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:04.280
exemplifies sort of the
flavor of the book.

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:06.010
And that's the fashion
industry.

00:04:06.010 --> 00:04:08.960
So I'm going to guess that a
lot of you are not frequent

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:10.960
shoppers at Faviana.

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:13.610
Maybe you've been to
other stores--

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:15.520
so Faviana actually does
not even have a

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:16.260
brick-and-mortar store.

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:17.170
It's just a website.

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:18.589
They sell to other places.

00:04:18.589 --> 00:04:20.170
And you directly
order dresses.

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:22.680
But what's important about
Faviana, and you can see from

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.780
this website, is its
whole business

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:28.080
model is knocking off.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:33.340
So typically, one of their
big business areas are

00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:35.170
girls going to a prom.

00:04:35.170 --> 00:04:37.640
They go to one of these
pictures, they say oh, I saw

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:40.250
Angelina Jolie on the red carpet
at the Oscars last year

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:40.990
wearing this great dress.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:42.900
I want to have that dress.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:44.690
And then they can order it.

00:04:44.690 --> 00:04:46.650
It's not the same dress.

00:04:46.650 --> 00:04:48.220
It's going to be significantly
cheaper.

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:49.945
It might be a few hundred
dollars rather than a few

00:04:49.945 --> 00:04:52.300
thousand dollars or maybe even
tens of thousands of dollars

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:52.830
for the original.

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:54.730
It's not going to look
exactly the same.

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:56.750
The material might not
be exactly the same.

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:59.800
But it's a pretty
close facsimile.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:03.670
And that's their basic
business model.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:05.980
You can see similar sorts of
things if you walk into

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:06.750
Forever 21.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:08.220
Now, some of you may
have done that.

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:10.780
So if you go into a Forever
21, you'll see lots of

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:13.920
examples of knocked-off
designs.

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:16.250
And I want to pause for a moment
just to explain what I

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:18.900
mean by a knockoff versus
a counterfeit.

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:23.100
So if you buy a dress or a pair
of sunglasses in a place

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:25.720
like Santee Alley downtown or
Canal Street in New York, and

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:28.490
you see a fake label that says,
like, Prada, or maybe

00:05:28.490 --> 00:05:32.100
Prado, or some version like
that, that's a counterfeit.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:33.870
So what they're trying to do is
say, hey, you think you're

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:36.995
buying this Prada handbag or
pair of sunglasses, but you're

00:05:36.995 --> 00:05:37.310
really not.

00:05:37.310 --> 00:05:39.498
You're buying something else.

00:05:39.498 --> 00:05:41.520
That's counterfeit, and that's
really dealing with trademark

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:44.060
and the brand.

00:05:44.060 --> 00:05:47.070
What we're talking about here
is the actual design.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:50.400
So the look of the dress that
Angelina Jolie's wearing in

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.820
that picture, or Megan Fox, the
way it's cut, the design,

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:55.060
the shape, et cetera--

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:59.310
those things are all completely
legal to copy.

00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:02.890
So the counterfeit example
is absolutely illegal.

00:06:02.890 --> 00:06:05.500
The design, however, is
completely legal to copy.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:08.070
And it's been that way in the
United States forever.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:11.760
We've never protected fashion
designs from copying.

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:18.300
So the fashion industry has for
decades operated without

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:20.830
any effective intellectual
property protection over its

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:23.680
core product, which is the
look of the actual--

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:25.370
and it's not just dresses,
obviously.

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:27.670
Any kind of clothing, accessory,
and so forth,

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:29.900
without any protection
for that.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:32.380
And what's interesting
about that is it's a

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:33.790
pretty vibrant industry.

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:36.050
And I want to just take a
moment just to say that

00:06:36.050 --> 00:06:39.760
knocking off is not limited to
companies like Faviana or, for

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:40.840
that matter, Forever 21.

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:44.365
So this is drawn from "US
Weekly" a few months ago.

00:06:44.365 --> 00:06:47.910
And you can find features like
this in a lot of these kinds

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:49.490
of magazines.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:52.130
So one actress is wearing
the original.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:53.350
One's wearing a copy.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:55.460
The copy's always
much cheaper.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:56.400
I shouldn't say always--

00:06:56.400 --> 00:06:57.830
often much cheaper.

00:06:57.830 --> 00:06:58.780
It depends.

00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:01.420
But typically, it is
significantly cheaper.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:04.440
And these kind of knockoffs
are everywhere.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:07.570
And since I mentioned Forever
21, I'll give you an example,

00:07:07.570 --> 00:07:11.500
in a moment, of a Forever
21 example.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:14.060
But so you can see these outfits
look pretty similar.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:16.750
From a distance, you could
not tell the difference.

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:19.130
So these copies are
quite similar.

00:07:19.130 --> 00:07:22.800
Now again, just to step back
to where I began, I think

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:24.930
you've all seen this warning.

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:28.780
And this warning gets at the
underlying principles of our

00:07:28.780 --> 00:07:30.970
system of intellectual
property.

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:34.730
So why is it not only illegal
but, in fact, a criminal

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:36.450
offense to make a copy?

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:39.190
Because we think that protecting
against copies is

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:42.530
such a significant factor in
our intellectual property

00:07:42.530 --> 00:07:44.960
system that we have to police
it in that way.

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:48.580
So that makes the fashion
industry really unusual--

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:50.800
though it's only one chapter
in the book, and I'll go

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:52.400
through some of the
other examples.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:53.300
It's not unique.

00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:54.760
It's just unusual.

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:56.560
So I mentioned Forever 21.

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:59.360
So this is an example we talk
about in "The Knockoff

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:03.940
Economy." So the dress on
the left, I believe--

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:05.620
I can't even tell, because they
look so much alike-- is

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:06.160
the original.

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:09.340
The one on the right is the
Forever 21 version.

00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:13.270
So the original sold for maybe
$400 a few years ago.

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:15.810
The copy sold for about $40.

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:20.080
Paris Hilton wore the dress on
David Letterman, and all of a

00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:22.350
sudden, orders started flooding
in to Forever 21.

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:23.600
It became a big thing.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:25.680
But again, the designers
could do absolutely

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:27.360
nothing about it.

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:29.670
That's just the way
of the industry.

00:08:29.670 --> 00:08:31.900
OK, so how does fashion work?

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:35.600
What makes it work
as a system?

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:38.549
To make the point clear, why
is it that this kind of

00:08:38.549 --> 00:08:41.470
copying is not destroying the
incentive to create in the

00:08:41.470 --> 00:08:44.090
fashion industry in the way that
our intellectual property

00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:45.070
system supposes?

00:08:45.070 --> 00:08:47.430
And I'll give you two
basic answers.

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:49.620
There's a much longer version
of this, obviously, in the

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:51.810
book, but two basic things
to think about.

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:56.590
The first is that fashion has
some special qualities that

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.320
are grounded in the fact that
it is something that's

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:04.210
expressive and public and has
a status component to it.

00:09:04.210 --> 00:09:06.360
Now, a lot of us don't pay
attention to fashion.

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:08.490
We don't really care about it.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:09.850
That's sort of one end
of the spectrum.

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.530
There's a middle group of people
who do care a little

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:12.620
bit, and then there's
a small group of

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:14.080
people who care a lot.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:16.370
So people divide up
in those ways.

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:19.400
For people who really care
about fashion, this

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:22.930
status-expressive component is
really significant for the

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:23.900
following reason.

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:28.000
So we've known for, really,
centuries that things come

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.550
into style, and they
go out of style.

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:32.120
So Shakespeare talked about the
fashion wearing out more

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:34.990
apparel than the man in "Much
Ado About Nothing."

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:36.990
And what Shakespeare was getting
at was the idea that

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:38.310
you don't typically
wear your clothes

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:39.220
until they're destroyed.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:42.500
You wear them until you're kind
of sick of them, or until

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:43.850
somebody tells you you've
really got to

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.010
get rid of that thing.

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:50.110
And you get something new, or
you just feel like it's time.

00:09:50.110 --> 00:09:52.220
So that's how most of us change
our clothes, for the

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:54.570
most part, especially in a place
like the United States.

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:56.090
It's not because we're
wearing them out.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:58.610
It's because there's something
new out there, some

00:09:58.610 --> 00:09:59.810
new style out there.

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:01.680
So things come into style, they
go out of style, that's

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:02.470
the fashion cycle.

00:10:02.470 --> 00:10:06.020
That's been long recognized.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:08.450
What's important, and I think
relatively unrecognized--

00:10:08.450 --> 00:10:11.840
this is what we emphasize in our
book-- is that the freedom

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:15.130
to copy that flows from the fact
that our copyright law

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:18.960
does not address fashion, means
that that fashion cycle

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:20.820
can turn even faster.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:23.900
And the reason that it turns
even faster is that once a

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:27.720
dress like this comes into style
and Forever 21 copies

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:31.810
it, now the original might have
sold a few hundred, maybe

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.900
even a thousand, maybe a couple
of thousand copies.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:35.920
That's it.

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:39.060
But the copy sold tens of
thousands, maybe hundreds of

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:39.960
thousands of versions.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:43.040
So it spreads out into the
marketplace very quickly.

00:10:43.040 --> 00:10:45.760
And so now the people who spent
$400 on the original

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:48.890
start to see, maybe, the girl
down the street wearing the

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:49.630
$40 version.

00:10:49.630 --> 00:10:51.360
And they're kind of annoyed
about that, and they're

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:52.690
annoyed that it's everywhere.

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:56.030
And we spoke to the designers
of this original dress, and

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:56.640
they were peeved.

00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:59.510
And they talked about customers
coming in and

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:02.765
complaining that they had chosen
it for some event or a

00:11:02.765 --> 00:11:05.640
bridesmaid's dress or whatever
it might be, and now the

00:11:05.640 --> 00:11:08.690
specialness had been destroyed
by the copy.

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:10.460
So what effect does that have?

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:13.050
Well, it drives people to
go and say, well, I want

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:13.390
something new.

00:11:13.390 --> 00:11:13.880
I want something different.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.660
I'm not going to keep wearing
this dress anymore.

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:16.740
So in other words,
it makes that

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:18.580
fashion cycle turn faster.

00:11:18.580 --> 00:11:20.910
And so designers then have to
offer something faster.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:24.840
So in fashion, unlike
technology, the new, new thing

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:26.350
is not better in any way.

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:27.600
It's just different.

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:30.590
Clothing doesn't improve
in any meaningful way.

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:33.865
Sometimes people come up with a
new fabric that repels heat

00:11:33.865 --> 00:11:36.040
or water or something--
that's unusual.

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:38.970
Most of it is just
sort of changes.

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:43.200
And so how you get people to
get a new phone is you tell

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:46.340
them, hey, this newer phone has
a million features that

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:48.860
your old phone didn't have, so
get rid of your old phone.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:52.960
With clothing, you have to
have some other means to

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:56.160
induce that desire for
consumers to buy.

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:58.820
And that's partly driven
by the ability to copy.

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:01.350
And that relates to a second
point, which is trends.

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:02.910
So if we think about the fashion
industry, it's a

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:04.520
trend-driven industry.

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:06.990
There are trends, and if you
read magazines like "US

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.170
Weekly" or "Vogue"--

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:10.880
again, I'm going to guess
a lot of us don't.

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:13.730
But if you do, if you look
in those, you'll see that

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:15.970
there'll be discussions of
what's in style this season,

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:18.090
what's coming in next season,
what was on the runway, et

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:19.170
cetera, et cetera.

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.620
So trends are a major
part of fashion.

00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:24.580
And if you think about a trend,
a trend is just a

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:26.890
series of things that
look alike.

00:12:26.890 --> 00:12:28.960
That's what makes it a trend.

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:31.270
It's a bunch of things that
are similar in some way.

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:33.990
So here again, the freedom to
copy that our copyright system

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:38.560
allows the fashion industry also
allows trends to develop.

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:41.370
And as those trends develop,
they give people something to

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:44.610
latch onto if they want to
be stylishly dressed.

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:47.210
So they could say, OK, the trend
this season is X. I'm

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:48.430
going to follow X.

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:53.130
So it also helps with the kind
of information gathering issue

00:12:53.130 --> 00:12:54.300
for fashion consumers.

00:12:54.300 --> 00:12:56.280
What is it you buy in a
marketplace that offers

00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:57.670
thousands of choices?

00:12:57.670 --> 00:12:59.710
Trends help kind
of define that.

00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:03.990
So the bottom line is copying
has a paradoxical effect in

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:04.790
the fashion industry.

00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:07.090
It doesn't drive
out creativity.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:08.380
It actually promotes it.

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:10.940
It acts like this turbocharger,
spinning that

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:13.890
fashion cycle faster and faster
and leading designers

00:13:13.890 --> 00:13:15.860
to come up with new designs
even faster.

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:20.360
So far from destroying
innovation, it's promoting it.

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:23.800
Now, fashion is not alone
in doing that.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:25.970
Here's an example of something
I'm guessing a lot of you have

00:13:25.970 --> 00:13:28.060
eaten at some point
or another, right?

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:30.280
So the molten chocolate cake.

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:33.260
If you look at the world of
cuisine, it's surprisingly

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:36.100
similar to the fashion world.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:39.150
The molten chocolate cake,
whether the recipe or the cake

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:43.430
itself, is unprotected by
copyright or patent.

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:46.530
So for example, a recipe
is, strictly speaking,

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:48.340
uncopyrightable.

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:51.520
So if you buy a cookbook, the
cookbook is copyrightable.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:54.200
And the stuff around the recipe,
where the chef says,

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:56.340
well, I was vacationing in
Tuscany, and I saw this

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:57.240
wonderful--

00:13:57.240 --> 00:13:58.750
that kind of stuff is
all copyrightable.

00:13:58.750 --> 00:14:01.110
But the actual recipe
itself is not.

00:14:01.110 --> 00:14:03.610
So that's why you can go
online to a place like

00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:06.060
Epicurious or cooks.com or any
of these websites and find

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:08.080
tons and tons of examples
of recipes.

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:09.360
Totally legal.

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:11.420
Likewise, you can walk
into a restaurant and

00:14:11.420 --> 00:14:12.870
say, I love this dish.

00:14:12.870 --> 00:14:15.290
And if you're a good chef, you
can reverse engineer that

00:14:15.290 --> 00:14:17.370
dish, figure out what the
components are, what the

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:20.180
techniques are, and then make
it yourself, and maybe even

00:14:20.180 --> 00:14:22.240
serve it at the restaurant
across the street.

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:25.440
Totally legal to do.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:29.710
And as a result, things like
this get invented and then

00:14:29.710 --> 00:14:31.070
migrate around.

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:33.990
So there's a little bit of a
dispute over who the true

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:36.900
inventor of the molten
chocolate cake is.

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:39.260
But many people would place it
in a restaurant on the Upper

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:42.860
East Side of Manhattan in
sort of the late 1980s.

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:45.000
And now you can find
this in Chili's.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.610
And you can, in fact, find the
Chili's recipe online.

00:14:47.610 --> 00:14:50.710
You can find it in almost
any restaurant today.

00:14:50.710 --> 00:14:53.210
If you've had miso-glazed
black cod--

00:14:53.210 --> 00:14:55.580
I'm guessing some people
have eaten that dish.

00:14:55.580 --> 00:14:59.550
Somebody invented that somewhere
in Japan, and it

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:00.130
spreads out.

00:15:00.130 --> 00:15:01.910
And there are example after
example like that.

00:15:01.910 --> 00:15:06.590
So nothing stops the
copying of cuisine.

00:15:06.590 --> 00:15:08.290
Does it mean that copying
has driven out

00:15:08.290 --> 00:15:09.400
creativity in cuisine?

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:09.810
No.

00:15:09.810 --> 00:15:11.030
I think actually the opposite.

00:15:11.030 --> 00:15:14.560
I think today we live in
probably the most creative

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:17.170
time ever for cuisine.

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:20.020
And there's incredibly inventive
cooking going on.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:21.920
So there's some very basic and
delicious and excellent

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:23.170
cooking going on.

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:26.240
If any of you have been to
Bazaar on La Cienega, you know

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:27.240
what I'm talking about, right?

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:30.720
So people are coming up with
extremely creative dishes

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:34.140
using new techniques,
in some cases.

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:36.130
And just as a footnote, some
of those techniques can be

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:39.110
patented, but most aren't.

00:15:39.110 --> 00:15:41.560
But the dishes themselves, as
long as you can figure out how

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:42.910
to do it and you have
the right tools, you

00:15:42.910 --> 00:15:44.610
can recreate them.

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:48.800
So just like in the fashion
world, the culinary world has

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:50.550
not been destroyed by copying.

00:15:50.550 --> 00:15:52.740
And in fact, if you talk to
chefs-- and in the book, we

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:56.850
discuss many examples and also
quote from many of the chefs

00:15:56.850 --> 00:16:00.610
that we interviewed, great chefs
here and in New York.

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:04.380
And also, we draw on some other
studies that looked at

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:07.150
places like Paris.

00:16:07.150 --> 00:16:09.840
If you talk to chefs, they're
very divided on this issue.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:13.600
Some of them feel that they're
artists, much like fashion

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:14.580
designers sometimes feel.

00:16:14.580 --> 00:16:17.330
They're artists, and their art
should be protected the same

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:20.330
as music would be protected,
the same as poetry is

00:16:20.330 --> 00:16:23.340
protected, the same as novels
are protected, et cetera, et

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:25.090
cetera-- paintings.

00:16:25.090 --> 00:16:27.890
Others think-- and I think this
is the majority view--

00:16:27.890 --> 00:16:33.720
that innovation is assisted by
an open framework, which you

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:40.360
can view as roughly akin to a
kind of open-source model of

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:40.900
innovation.

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:44.210
So rather than saying, I own
this molten chocolate cake,

00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:46.820
and you cannot copy it, or for
that matter, produce anything

00:16:46.820 --> 00:16:49.730
that's substantially similar,
which is our legal standard

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:53.230
for copyright, to it, instead
a lot of chefs believe that

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:56.400
the ability to share and to
trade and to tweak and to

00:16:56.400 --> 00:17:00.480
improve upon what others have
done actually produces more

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:02.810
creativity and better products
in the long run.

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:07.060
And that openness is promotive
of innovation, not destructive

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:08.750
of innovation.

00:17:08.750 --> 00:17:12.119
So the world of chefs
is quite similar.

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:13.750
Let me just add one other
point about chefs.

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:14.960
I mentioned Paris.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:16.080
One of the things we talk about
in the "The Knockoff

00:17:16.080 --> 00:17:19.910
Economy" is a very interesting
study by two people at MIT who

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:22.859
went and interviewed high-end
chefs in Paris.

00:17:22.859 --> 00:17:25.290
These are chefs that had
Michelin-starred restaurants.

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:27.510
If you know about the Michelin
system, you know even one star

00:17:27.510 --> 00:17:28.660
is a huge deal.

00:17:28.660 --> 00:17:31.600
So these all had at least
one star or more.

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:35.810
And these chefs had a system
of social norms amongst

00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:38.630
themselves, so the
study argued--

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:40.780
and we think it's a
well-done study--

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:44.060
that constrain the types of
copying that took place, but

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:47.850
really focused not so much on
restricting copying but on how

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:48.520
you copied.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:50.480
And the key issue is
really attribution.

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:53.400
It was perfectly fine to copy a
cake or much more elaborate

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:56.270
dishes, as long as you
attributed it to the

00:17:56.270 --> 00:17:57.690
originator.

00:17:57.690 --> 00:17:59.895
So it's a little bit like the
labeling issue I talked about

00:17:59.895 --> 00:18:00.630
with fashion.

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:04.170
As long as you don't tweak the
trademark, that's fine.

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:05.750
So I'll come back to this
issue of brands

00:18:05.750 --> 00:18:10.100
versus designs later.

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:12.720
This is a football formation.

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:15.810
Now again, football is not an
industry we normally think of

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:18.130
as being driven by
or undergirded by

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:19.620
intellectual property.

00:18:19.620 --> 00:18:24.030
But actually, the NFL has been
involved in a lot of IP cases.

00:18:24.030 --> 00:18:25.990
They have huge investments
in their brands.

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:28.320
They have very good and very
high-priced lawyers.

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:31.370
They know all about intellectual
property.

00:18:31.370 --> 00:18:37.210
However, what they haven't done
is been able to copyright

00:18:37.210 --> 00:18:41.270
a formation, even though in
theory, there is a category

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:43.650
for choreographic works in our
copyright statute in the

00:18:43.650 --> 00:18:44.800
United States.

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:47.520
And a football formation is
a form of choreography.

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:49.160
It just happens to involve
throwing a ball and hitting

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:50.950
people, rather than dancing
on a stage.

00:18:50.950 --> 00:18:52.790
But is choreographic.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:54.240
No one's been able to
successfully make this

00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:56.650
argument to the copyright
office.

00:18:56.650 --> 00:18:58.250
But substantively, they're
quite similar.

00:18:58.250 --> 00:18:59.700
So put that aside
for a moment.

00:18:59.700 --> 00:19:04.490
The fact is, formations and
plays are fully copyable.

00:19:04.490 --> 00:19:06.830
Totally legal to copy a
formation and play.

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:09.720
Now again, does that stop
football coaches from coming

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:11.010
up with new formations?

00:19:11.010 --> 00:19:11.710
No.

00:19:11.710 --> 00:19:14.930
So we go through many examples
in the book where we talk

00:19:14.930 --> 00:19:16.120
about things like--

00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:19.070
some of them are very simple,
like the no-huddle offense,

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:22.030
where as it sort of suggests,
there's no huddle.

00:19:22.030 --> 00:19:24.290
You just go from play to play
to play very quickly.

00:19:24.290 --> 00:19:25.600
Quite effective.

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:29.230
To things that are more
complicated and variants on a

00:19:29.230 --> 00:19:32.740
theme, so the spread, the spread
option, et cetera,

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:35.070
pioneered both at the college
level, sometimes even at the

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:38.500
high school level,
and in the NFL.

00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:42.570
Now again, why is it that the
ability to copy a formation

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:46.420
doesn't stop coaches or
constrain them from creating

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:49.700
the way that our copyright
system assumes in most cases?

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:52.800
We think the answer is really
two-fold, and I'm going to

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:54.940
focus on one in particular.

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:58.070
The first is football is an
intensely competitive

00:19:58.070 --> 00:19:59.040
enterprise.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:01.590
So particularly when you're
talking about college football

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:04.050
and pro football, winning
or losing a single

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:05.550
game is a big deal.

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:07.970
And especially if that game is
something like the Super Bowl,

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:12.230
that's a career-winning issue.

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:14.420
There's also a powerful
first-mover

00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:15.880
advantage in football.

00:20:15.880 --> 00:20:19.370
So if you think about a
formation or a play, it's easy

00:20:19.370 --> 00:20:22.180
to say, hey, I see this play,
I understand it, I'm

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:23.240
going to copy it.

00:20:23.240 --> 00:20:26.210
What's difficult to do is
actually to get your team to

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:29.610
execute it well, and in some
cases, to build the proper

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:32.690
team that can execute this
type of play well.

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:34.560
So in other words, you may
need bigger or smaller

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:37.350
players, faster players,
different types of players.

00:20:37.350 --> 00:20:40.070
That may take some
time to recruit.

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:42.990
So that's a marginal issue, but
it's not insignificant.

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:44.070
You also have to train.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:45.230
You have to perfect it.

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:48.960
So there's a period of time
between the moment a new play

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:52.540
is unveiled on a field and the
time that competitors can

00:20:52.540 --> 00:20:55.480
really use it to their
advantage.

00:20:55.480 --> 00:20:57.300
So economists call that
first-mover advantage.

00:20:57.300 --> 00:20:59.480
We see that in a lot
of industries.

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:03.950
And here, that natural
advantage, no laws involved in

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:07.300
that, gives enough of an
incentive, especially in a

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:11.000
very competitive industry, for
coaches to continue to create.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.310
So here again, we see creativity
coupled to copying,

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:19.060
and the two seem to fit
very well together.

00:21:19.060 --> 00:21:22.200
Now, is that a unique thing?

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:24.550
I'm going to argue
that it's not.

00:21:24.550 --> 00:21:25.470
I'm going to just play
you something

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:26.540
quickly from this guy.

00:21:26.540 --> 00:21:26.860
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:26.860 --> 00:21:28.190
-Good artists copy.

00:21:28.190 --> 00:21:30.090
Great artists steal.

00:21:30.090 --> 00:21:34.040
And we have always been
shameless about

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:35.700
stealing great ideas.

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.050
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

